    active_lock_reason: null,
    body:
      '## Summary\r\n\r\nBe able to specify a whitelist of validators to pre-jail when I export my state to JSON. \r\n\r\n## Problem Definition\r\n\r\nHard forking a network is a necessary use case, sometimes.\r\n\r\nOption A.\r\n\r\nCoordinate with every validator to get them to get all their delegations removed so they are no longer validators (ie: have 0 tokens bonded). Then, once they are all unbonded, hard fork, and let them join again as validators by adding stake.\r\n\r\nOption B.\r\n\r\nCoordinate with every validator to set a time when you halt the old network and start up the new network. This requires alot of orchestration effort and is not ideal. \r\n\r\nOption C. \r\n\r\nPre-jail all validators but the ones we intend to hard fork immediately (the validators we "own"). Once the hard fork is running, they can unjail themselves. \r\n\r\nLooking at these options, C is the happiest path. No orchestration needed. Validators who failed to upgrade right away do not face being jailed (and slashed). It makes total sense to prejail all validators but your own when you start the new network in a hard fork.\r\n\r\n## Proposal\r\n\r\nAdd a pre-jail flag to export that allows a comma-separated list of valopers (validator operator address) that I can pre-jail as part of the export.\r\n\r\n____\r\n\r\n#### For Admin Use\r\n\r\n- [ ] Not duplicate issue\r\n- [ ] Appropriate labels applied\r\n- [ ] Appropriate contributors tagged\r\n- [ ] Contributor assigned/self-assigned\r\n',
    performed_via_github_app: null,
